<section class='hero hero--page'>
    <div class='u-wrapper'>
        <p class='hero__eyebrow'>The case for JMAP</p>
        <h1 class='hero__h1'>Why JMAP?</h1>
        <p class='hero__sub'>
            IMAP turns 40 this year. The case for replacing it — grounded in benchmarks, implementation experience, and
            the realities of modern email infrastructure.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

{% capture pageContent %}
<article class='u-article'>{{ content }}</article>
<div class='faq'>
    <h2 class='faq__h2' id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details class='faq__details'>
        <summary class='faq__summary'>
            What is JMAP?
            <span class='faq__expand'>
                {% include icons/plus.liquid %}
            </span>
        </summary>
        <div class='faq__answer'>
            <p>
                JMAP (JSON Meta Application Protocol) is an open IETF standard for synchronising mail,
                calendars, and contacts between a client and server. It replaces IMAP with a protocol built
                on HTTPS and JSON, with efficient batch requests and real-time push updates built in.
            </p>
            <p>
                JMAP is standardised as
                <a href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8620' target='_blank'>RFC 8620</a> (core) and
                <a href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8621' target='_blank'>RFC 8621</a> (mail).
            </p>
        </div>
    </details>
    <details class='faq__details'>
        <summary class='faq__summary'>
            Is JMAP a replacement for IMAP?
            <span class='faq__expand'>
                {% include icons/plus.liquid %}
            </span>
        </summary>
        <div class='faq__answer'>
            <p>
                Yes, for client/server email access. JMAP covers everything IMAP does &mdash; reading,
                searching, moving, flagging, and sending email &mdash; with a much cleaner and more
                efficient API. JMAP also replaces POP3, client-side SMTP, CardDAV, and CalDAV.
            </p>
            <p>
                JMAP does not replace server-to-server SMTP. Email servers still use SMTP to route messages
                between domains.
            </p>
        </div>
    </details>
    <details class='faq__details'>
        <summary class='faq__summary'>
            Which email providers support JMAP?
            <span class='faq__expand'>
                {% include icons/plus.liquid %}
            </span>
        </summary>
        <div class='faq__answer'>
            <p>
                <strong>Fastmail</strong> is the largest JMAP provider and was instrumental in developing
                the standard &mdash; their entire web and mobile client runs on JMAP.
                <strong>Stalwart Mail Server</strong> is a modern open-source server with complete JMAP
                support. <strong>Apache James</strong> and <strong>Cyrus IMAP</strong> both support JMAP.
            </p>
        </div>
    </details>
    <details class='faq__details'>
        <summary class='faq__summary'>
            Is JMAP stable enough to build on?
            <span class='faq__expand'>
                {% include icons/plus.liquid %}
            </span>
        </summary>
        <div class='faq__answer'>
            <p>
                Yes. RFC 8620 and RFC 8621 are published IETF standards and will not change in
                backwards-incompatible ways. Fastmail has been running their entire production email service
                on JMAP since 2019.
            </p>
            <p>
                The contacts and calendars extensions are in active IETF development and close to final
                publication.
            </p>
        </div>
    </details>
    <details class='faq__details'>
        <summary class='faq__summary'>
            How does JMAP handle authentication?
            <span class='faq__expand'>
                {% include icons/plus.liquid %}
            </span>
        </summary>
        <div class='faq__answer'>
            <p>
                JMAP deliberately does not define its own authentication mechanism. It uses standard HTTP
                authentication &mdash; in practice, OAuth 2.0 with Bearer tokens. This means JMAP works with
                your existing identity infrastructure without any changes.
            </p>
        </div>
    </details>
    <details class='faq__details'>
        <summary class='faq__summary'>
            How does JMAP perform compared to IMAP?
            <span class='faq__expand'>
                {% include icons/plus.liquid %}
            </span>
        </summary>
        <div class='faq__answer'>
            <p>
                JMAP performs as well or better than IMAP in all tested scenarios. The resync benchmark
                showed JMAP completing in 0.8 seconds vs 7.4 seconds for Outlook and 35 seconds for
                Thunderbird (28,234 messages). iOS battery usage is 2&ndash;3&times; lower with JMAP vs IMAP
                without push support.
            </p>
            <p>
                Modern IMAP with all extensions enabled can be competitive, but this requires both the
                client and server to implement the right extensions &mdash; which is rarely the case in
                practice.
            </p>
        </div>
    </details>
</div>
{% endcapture %}

